<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE policyconfig PUBLIC
 "-//freedesktop//DTD PolicyKit Policy Configuration 1.0//EN"
 "http://www.freedesktop.org/standards/PolicyKit/1/policyconfig.dtd">
<policyconfig>
  <vendor>Bulwark</vendor>
  <vendor_url>https://github.com/vietanhdev/bulwark</vendor_url>

  <!--
    Bulwark's GUI elevates one thing: the privileged pass of `bulwarkctl scan`, to read root-only
    files (e.g. /etc/sudoers, /etc/shadow) for a full audit. It does this with `pkexec`, which uses
    the generic `org.freedesktop.policykit.exec` action below.

    (Note for editors: XML comments may not contain a double hyphen, so flag names like the one
    this pass is invoked with are written out in prose here rather than with their literal dashes.
    A double hyphen in this comment makes a strict XML parser reject the whole policy, which then
    silently never loads.)

    Two deliberate security choices:

    * auth_admin, NOT auth_admin_keep. `keep` caches the authorization for the *generic exec
      action* for several minutes, which means any other `pkexec <program>` in that window could
      be authorized without a fresh prompt. For a security tool that is the wrong trade: we would
      rather prompt on each privileged scan than leave a standing "run anything as root without
      asking" window open. Every elevation is therefore an explicit, per-action decision.

    * Which binary runs as root is decided by the app, not by this file. pkexec always runs the
      absolute path it is handed; Bulwark resolves that path only to the CLI bundled beside the
      app executable (canonicalized, no environment override) — see `resolve_cli_binary` in
      apps/bulwark-app/src-tauri/src/lib.rs. The `exec.path` annotation on the shared exec action
      is not an enforcement mechanism in polkit, so it is intentionally omitted here to avoid
      implying a guarantee this file does not provide.
  -->
  <action id="org.freedesktop.policykit.exec">
    <description>Run the privileged subset of a Bulwark scan</description>
    <message>Authentication is required for Bulwark to read root-only files (e.g. /etc/sudoers)</message>
    <defaults>
      <allow_any>auth_admin</allow_any>
      <allow_inactive>auth_admin</allow_inactive>
      <allow_active>auth_admin</allow_active>
    </defaults>
    <annotate key="org.freedesktop.policykit.exec.allow_gui">true</annotate>
  </action>
</policyconfig>
